Ennius had been able with rude vigour to depict the early history of Rome, to lay down a model of heroic verse for his successors, and to bequeath them a considerable vocabulary. But the language was still, as Lucretius thrice over complains2, a very imperfect vehicle for the discussion of political, moral, and metaphysical ideas.
